        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>GBP categories</strong> are predefined business classifications on Google Business Profile that tell Google what your business does and control which local searches surface your listing. Every listing requires <strong>one primary category</strong> and can add up to 9 secondary categories from a closed list of roughly <strong>4,000 options</strong>. According to Whitespark, GBP categories are the single most influential Map Pack ranking factor — more than reviews, more than citations.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Ranking factor</div>
            <div class="tms-value">#1 Map Pack</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Total options</div>
            <div class="tms-value">~4,000</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Local SEO campaigns often invest in reviews, citations, and content while leaving the highest-leverage lever untouched — the primary GBP category. Pick the wrong one and no amount of citation building will fix it.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What are GBP categories?</h2>
        <p>GBP categories are structured classifications from Google\u2019s taxonomy that describe what a business does. Each listing must select one primary category and can optionally add up to nine secondary categories. Together they tell Google which searches your listing is eligible to appear for.</p>
        <p>According to Whitespark\u2019s Local Search Ranking Factors survey, "GBP categories are the single most influential ranking factor for Map Pack visibility. More than reviews. More than citations."</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why the primary matters most</div>
          <p>The primary category is the single most weighted signal Google uses to decide which local queries your business ranks for. Secondary categories widen the query set but carry <strong>much less ranking weight</strong>. Switch your primary and rankings can change in a matter of days.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why GBP categories matter</h2>
        <p>Four reasons categories are the first thing to audit in any local SEO engagement:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>#1 local ranking signal.</strong> Primary category ranks as the top Map Pack ranking factor in the industry\u2019s most cited survey.</li>
          <li><strong>Controls search visibility.</strong> A business categorised as "Dentist" cannot rank for "orthodontist near me" without adding that category. Wrong category = invisible for the query.</li>
          <li><strong>Unlocks GBP features.</strong> Restaurants get menu options, hotels get booking buttons, service businesses unlock service-area settings — all driven by category.</li>
          <li><strong>Influences Google Ads matching.</strong> Categories affect Local Services Ads eligibility and matching. A wrong category can quietly block ad delivery.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How GBP categories work</h2>
        <p>Google treats primary and secondary categories very differently. Understanding the weight difference is what separates a working local SEO strategy from a noisy one.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># A dental practice choosing categories</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Primary:</span> <span class="uf-new">Dentist</span> <span class="uf-comment">// heaviest ranking weight</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Secondary:</span> Cosmetic Dentist<br>
          <span class="uf-label">Secondary:</span> Teeth Whitening Service<br>
          <span class="uf-label">Secondary:</span> Dental Implants Provider<br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Primary drives "dentist near me" ranking</span><br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Secondaries expand to whitening / implant queries</span>
        </div>

        <h3>Primary category</h3>
        <p>The most weighted signal. Visible on the listing under the business name. Best practice: pick the most specific option that accurately describes your core service.</p>

        <h3>Secondary categories</h3>
        <p>Up to 9 additional categories that expand visibility for related searches. They help but carry a fraction of the primary\u2019s weight. Only add ones that genuinely describe services you offer.</p>

        <h3>Semantic matching</h3>
        <p>Google matches categories beyond literal interpretations. A "Pizza Restaurant" listing can appear for "pizza delivery", "best pizza", or "Italian food near me" because Google understands the semantic neighbourhood of the category.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Types of GBP categories</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
