          <span class="uf-new">Switched to:</span> Search Engine Optimization Service<br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">+40% GBP impressions within 30 days</span><br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Same business, same website, only the category changed</span>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-related">GBP categories vs GBP attributes — different jobs</h2>
        <p>Both are structured metadata on your profile. They answer different questions.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Categories define</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>What your business fundamentally does</li>
              <li>Which core searches you rank for</li>
              <li>Which UI features your listing unlocks</li>
              <li>Which attribute options are available</li>
              <li>Your competitive set in the Map Pack</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Attributes describe</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Specific features (Wi-Fi, outdoor seating)</li>
              <li>Accessibility and payment options</li>
              <li>Identity (women-owned, veteran-owned)</li>
              <li>Filtered-search eligibility</li>
              <li>Experience signals (cozy, romantic)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for GBP categories</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Pick the most specific primary category available.</strong> "Cosmetic Dentist" beats "Dentist" if it accurately describes your core service. Specific = less competition + better relevance.</li>
          <li><strong>Research competitor categories in the Map Pack.</strong> Use tools like GMB Everywhere or PlePer to see the primary category of the top 3 businesses ranking for your target query. If they all use the same one, you probably should too.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit quarterly.</strong> Google adds new categories throughout the year — a new option may be a better fit than your current one.</li>
          <li><strong>Avoid irrelevant secondary categories.</strong> They dilute your relevance signal. Only add secondaries that genuinely describe services you provide.</li>
          <li><strong>Align website content with claimed categories.</strong> If you claim "Emergency Plumber", the website should have an emergency plumbing page. Google cross-checks entity signals.</li>
          <li><strong>Use 3–5 categories, not 10.</strong> More is not automatically better. Extra weak categories can dilute the primary signal.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep one primary category per listing.</strong> Do not split your business across multiple listings unless you have physically separate locations or genuinely distinct departments.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — picking a generic primary</div>
          <p>Businesses default to broad categories like "Marketing Agency" instead of specific ones like "Search Engine Optimization Service" because they want to "rank for everything". They rank for nothing well. Specific primary categories consistently out-rank generic ones on the queries that convert.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common GBP category mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Picking a generic primary category</strong> — competitive but low-intent. Specific beats generic every time.</li>
          <li><strong>Stacking 10 unrelated secondaries</strong> — dilutes the primary signal and adds nothing.</li>
          <li><strong>Never re-auditing</strong> — new categories added by Google go unused.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring competitor categories</strong> — the top-3 primary categories in your Map Pack are the market\u2019s answer to "which category ranks".</li>
          <li><strong>Website content doesn\u2019t match categories</strong> — creates entity confusion and weakens ranking signals.</li>
          <li><strong>Multiple listings for the same location to game categories</strong> — a spam violation that triggers suspension.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How many GBP categories can I add?</span>
